    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Was Erica Jong being ''deliberately titillating,'' as you say in your Feb. 23 Styles page article on the publisher Harold Evans's literary breakfasts, when she referred to ''Madame Bovary'' as a ''perpetual orgy''?</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Was Erica Jong being ''deliberately titillating,'' as you say in your Feb. 23 Styles page article on the publisher Harold Evans's literary breakfasts, when she referred to ''Madame Bovary'' as a ''perpetual orgy''?</p>
        <p>You may have found it so, but Ms. Jong was probably referring to Flaubert's letter to Mlle. Leroyer de Chantepie of Sept. 4, 1858: ''The one way of tolerating existence is to lose oneself in literature as in a perpetual orgy.'' That statement was taken as the epigraph of Mario Vargas Llosa's evocative study ''The Perpetual Orgy: Flaubert and Madame Bovary.'' But that is another breakfast entirely.</p>
        <p>NANCY LOCKE</p>
        <p>Detroit, Feb. 24, 1997</p>
      </block>
